                </p>
                <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">
                    The total soluble solids (TSS), measured in <strong>°Brix</strong>, represents the sugar concentration. Early harvest leads to sour, under-ripened fruit, while late harvest causes internal post-harvest fermentation, storage sponginess, and high pathogen susceptibility. 
                </p>
                <div class="bg-emerald-50 border-l-4 border-emerald-600 p-4 rounded-r-xl text-xs sm:text-sm text-emerald-900">
                    <p class="font-bold mb-1"><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-info mr-1"></i> Why Calculus / Derivatives?</p>
                    The absolute sugar level \( f(x) \) only tells us the current state. The <strong>first derivative \( f'(x) \)</strong> measures the *instantaneous accumulation rate* of sugars. By analyzing where \( f'(x) \) peaks (inflection point of \( f(x) \)) and where it drops to zero, food processors can schedule logistical chains to maximize premium fresh-cut fruit recovery.
